        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>Google Core Update</strong> is a broad, sitewide change to Google's core ranking algorithm that reassesses how content is evaluated across every topic and region. Google confirms core updates publicly and rolls them out <strong>3-4 times per year</strong>. They are recalibrations of what the algorithm values — not penalties for rule violations.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Frequency</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-4 per year</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Rollout window</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1-3 weeks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recovery timeline</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-6 months</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A core update is Google changing what "good content" means — not what "bad content" means. Sites that drop haven't broken any rules. Their content is just no longer the best answer under the new criteria.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a Google Core Update?</h2>
        <p>A Google Core Update is a broad, official update to the core ranking algorithm — the part of the system that decides which pages best answer a given query. Unlike targeted updates (spam, reviews, page experience), a core update touches how Google evaluates <em>every</em> site, in every language, across every topic.</p>
        <p>Google announces core updates on the Search Central blog and the @searchliaison account. Each is named by month and year: "March 2024 core update," "November 2024 core update," and so on. Between updates, Google's evaluation logic is relatively stable; during a core update, it shifts — and sites redistribute up or down accordingly.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance</div>
          <p>Google's guidance is unusually direct: "There's nothing wrong with pages that may perform less well in a core update. They haven't violated our webmaster guidelines... What we ask you to focus on is content improvement." Core updates are quality re-scoring, not spam enforcement.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why core updates matter</h2>
        <p>A single core update can reshape a site's revenue for a full quarter. Five reasons every SEO watches them closely:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Traffic swings are steep.</strong> A 30-70% drop in a week is not unusual for affected sites, and gains of similar size hit the beneficiaries.</li>
          <li><strong>Recovery is slow.</strong> The next core update — usually 3-6 months later — is the earliest chance to recover meaningfully.</li>
          <li><strong>Signals shift, not just weights.</strong> Google sometimes introduces new quality signals (originality, first-hand experience) during core updates, which changes what "good" looks like going forward.</li>
          <li><strong>YMYL sites carry higher risk.</strong> Health, finance, and legal sites face stricter <a href="/glossary/e-e-a-t/">E-E-A-T</a> expectations in every core update.</li>
          <li><strong>They shape the industry.</strong> Post-update case studies dictate what SEOs prioritize for the next 6-12 months.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How a core update works</h2>
        <p>A core update is a training-and-deployment cycle inside Google's ranking system, not a rule change published in a document. The mechanics:</p>
        <h3>Re-evaluation, not re-punishment</h3>
        <p>Google's ranking systems continuously score pages on hundreds of signals — helpfulness, expertise, freshness, page experience, on-page relevance. A core update recalibrates how those signals combine. The same page can now score higher or lower even if nothing on the page changed.</p>
        <h3>Rollout across 1-3 weeks</h3>
        <p>Updates deploy gradually across Google's data centers. Rankings fluctuate during the window. The "before" state and the "after" state are only clear once Google announces the rollout is complete.</p>
        <h3>Sitewide, not page-level</h3>
        <p>Core updates evaluate sites holistically. Sections of thin, unhelpful content can drag down the ranking of high-quality pages on the same domain. That's why site-level cleanup matters even when only some pages seem affected.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Major Google Core Updates since 2018</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Update</th><th>Date</th><th>What changed</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Medic Update</strong></td><td>Aug 2018</td><td>First named broad core update; hit YMYL health/finance hardest</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>March 2019 Core</strong></td><td>Mar 2019</td><td>Broad quality reassessment</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>January 2020 Core</strong></td><td>Jan 2020</td><td>Big swings in publishers, health, finance</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>May 2020 Core</strong></td><td>May 2020</td><td>Notable travel + hospitality shifts during COVID</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>December 2020 Core</strong></td><td>Dec 2020</td><td>Broad reassessment; delayed to late in year</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Helpful Content + March 2024 Core</strong></td><td>Mar 2024</td><td>Merged Helpful Content System into core; aggressive on scaled/AI content</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Aug 2024 Core</strong></td><td>Aug 2024</td><td>Recovery signals for small sites hit by prior updates</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Nov 2024 Core</strong></td><td>Nov 2024</td><td>Continued focus on originality and first-hand experience</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Mar/Jun 2025 Core</strong></td><td>2025</td><td>Ongoing quality re-scoring; further AI-content signals</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real core update examples</h2>
        <h3>1. A YMYL health site drops 62% in March 2024</h3>
        <p>An affiliate-driven supplement review site with no medical author credentials lost 62% of organic sessions inside 10 days of the March 2024 update. Content was accurate but generic. Recovery required rewriting under a named medical reviewer, adding first-hand product testing, and pruning 40% of the URL count.</p>
        <h3>2. An SMB HVAC blog gains 3x in August 2024</h3>
        <p>A local HVAC company's blog had ~4,000 sessions/month before August 2024. The August update explicitly aimed to restore small, independent sites unfairly hit by earlier rounds. Their traffic jumped to 12,400 sessions/month within two weeks — no on-page changes had been made.</p>
        <h3>3. AI-generated content site loses 90%+ in Sep 2023</h3>
        <p>A site publishing 500 AI-written articles per month across dozens of niches lost more than 90% of visibility during the September 2023 Helpful Content Update, and did not recover in subsequent core updates. Scaled, low-effort AI content is now an explicit downweight signal.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Core update vs Helpful Content Update — what's the difference?</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Core Update</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Broad recalibration of the entire ranking system</li>
              <li>Affects all queries, categories, and regions</li>
              <li>Confirmed by Google with names + dates</li>
              <li>Sitewide impact — high-quality pages can rise while thin ones drag them</li>
              <li>Recovery requires the next core update to see the change</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/helpful-content-update/">Helpful Content Update (now part of core)</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Originally a separate classifier for "content written for people, not search engines"</li>
              <li>Merged into the core system in March 2024</li>
              <li>Aggressively downgrades scaled AI and thin affiliate content</li>
              <li>Applied at the sitewide level</li>
              <li>Now moves with every core update, not on its own schedule</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices when responding to a core update</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Wait for the rollout to complete.</strong> Numbers swing throughout the window. Analyze only after Google announces the end.</li>
          <li><strong>Segment by page type and topic cluster.</strong> Losers rarely lose evenly — the pattern matters more than the total drop.</li>
          <li><strong>Run the drop through Google's helpful-content self-audit.</strong> The 32 questions Google publishes are the closest thing to a rubric.</li>
          <li><strong>Prune or rewrite thin pages.</strong> Sitewide quality signals drag everything down. Cutting weak pages can lift strong ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Strengthen author credentials.</strong> First-hand experience, real credentials, and byline pages carry more weight in each successive update.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix duplicate and low-differentiation content.</strong> Multiple pages targeting the same intent is a classic signal Google now downweights.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't chase the update — build for the next one.</strong> Recovery lands at the next core update, so the work has to be structural, not cosmetic.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — reverting a redesign</div>
          <p>Sites that lose traffic during a core update often blame a coincidental redesign or migration. Rolling back rarely helps. If Google's evaluation of your content quality changed, the design layer is a rounding error.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common core-update mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Making changes mid-rollout.</strong> Wait for the announced end date before touching anything.</li>
          <li><strong>Disavowing backlinks.</strong> No relationship to core update outcomes.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming it's technical.</strong> Core updates are about content quality, not crawl or schema issues.</li>
          <li><strong>Expecting overnight recovery.</strong> The next update is the earliest chance to see the impact of your fixes.</li>
          <li><strong>Adding more thin content.</strong> Volume without helpfulness makes the next update worse.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>Our team runs post-core-update audits that segment drops by cluster, topic, and page type — then rebuild the content around named authors, first-hand experience, and demonstrated <a href="/glossary/e-e-a-t/">E-E-A-T</a>. We prune what's dragging you down and rewrite what's close-to-ranking. The goal is a site Google's next update lifts, not one that limps sideways.</p>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Is a core update a penalty?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
